TY  - JOUR
AU  - Kini, Omesh
AU  - Williams, Ryan
AU  - Yin, Sirui
T1  - CEO Noncompete Agreements, Job Risk, and Compensation
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/10/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhaa103
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 34
IS  - 10
SP  - 4701
EP  - 4744
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - Using hand-collected data on CEO noncompete agreements (NCAs), we find that NCAs are less common when CEOs expect to incur greater personal costs from reduced job mobility and more common when firms expect to suffer greater economic harm if departing CEOs leave to work for a competitor. Additionally, turnover-performance sensitivity is stronger when CEOs have NCAs. Finally, total compensation and incentive pay are higher if CEOs have more enforceable NCAs. Our identification strategy exploits staggered state-level changes in NCA enforceability. Overall, our findings suggest that restrictions on job mobility have important implications for how CEOs are monitored and compensated.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhaa103
ER  - 



